WEBVTT

00:45.170 --> 00:49.633
<i>Do you, Boxy, take this air conditioner
to be your lawfully wedded...</i>

00:50.175 --> 00:52.052
<i>You can't go through with it, Boxy.</i>

00:52.052 --> 00:54.304
<i>For she is your sister.</i>

00:56.056 --> 00:57.307
<i>And my sister.</i>

00:58.267 --> 01:00.060
<i>And my wife!</i>

01:01.895 --> 01:03.188
<i>And my air conditioner!</i>

01:09.194 --> 01:12.114
Oh, there you are. Behold.

01:15.701 --> 01:18.453
What in the name of my ass
is going on here?

01:18.453 --> 01:22.207
The Academy of Inventors'
Annual Competition is approaching.

01:22.207 --> 01:26.587
So I've created the world's
most powerful sewing machine.

01:27.754 --> 01:29.798
That is an amazing invention.

01:29.798 --> 01:32.301
This isn't the invention, you boob.

01:32.301 --> 01:35.721
Let me just activate it
using my footnological marvel,

01:35.721 --> 01:37.306
the toelonger.

01:37.306 --> 01:39.141
It's glorious!

01:39.141 --> 01:41.685
That's not the invention, either.
Stop guessing.

01:47.524 --> 01:50.152
The theme of the competition
is recycling.

01:50.152 --> 01:53.071
So I'm attempting to recycle
old human parts

01:53.071 --> 01:56.617
into a new,
environmentally-friendly human.

01:56.617 --> 01:58.535
Hyello, Mr. Professorvich.

01:58.535 --> 02:01.163
Very extremely good catch for you today.

02:01.163 --> 02:03.790
Luckily was big railroad accident.

02:03.790 --> 02:06.585
I'll take a pound and a half of hand.

02:13.383 --> 02:15.802
Wow. Is that a flatlock seam?

02:15.802 --> 02:18.055
Why, thank you for noticing, Amy.

02:18.055 --> 02:21.350
It looks elegant
and minimizes blood loss.

02:23.185 --> 02:25.354
Now, the easy part.

02:42.579 --> 02:43.872
VoilÃ !

02:44.039 --> 02:47.167
Um, Professor? Most people have a head.

02:47.167 --> 02:49.461
Sure. The in-crowd.

02:49.461 --> 02:51.380
Look, you've come this far.

02:51.380 --> 02:54.716
You don't wanna lose the contest
over a few style points.

02:54.716 --> 02:58.679
Fine. Let's fancy it up with a head.

02:58.679 --> 03:01.849
The head is the part with the teeth
and the sneeze hole, right?

03:06.770 --> 03:08.939
Any of you presidents need a body?

03:08.939 --> 03:10.899
Can it hit a no-look jump shot?

03:11.066 --> 03:13.819
- Uh, sure.
- Then why does it need me?

03:16.655 --> 03:17.781
Good one, Mommy!

03:17.781 --> 03:21.243
Whoa! The Gallery of Supermodels!

03:21.410 --> 03:25.664
Ugh. Okay, but remember:
Their eyes are up here.

03:28.667 --> 03:32.296
Um, do any of you
lovely lady... People...

03:34.464 --> 03:37.467
Which of you indistinguishable
human heads wants a body?

03:37.467 --> 03:38.552
Is it tall?

03:38.552 --> 03:42.181
I miss doing runway shows
and intimidating short people.

03:42.181 --> 03:43.807
The left side's pretty tall.

03:43.807 --> 03:45.934
Trust me, it's attractive.

03:45.934 --> 03:48.854
It's got thick, luxurious hair
all over the place,

03:48.854 --> 03:51.565
and several legs that just won't quit.

03:51.565 --> 03:52.900
And one that will.

03:52.900 --> 03:54.026
I'll do it.

03:55.110 --> 03:56.195
Really?

03:56.195 --> 04:00.282
Of course, dear, it's not the body,
it's how you wear it.

04:00.657 --> 04:04.369
That's Cara Delevingne.
She invented eyebrows.

04:08.832 --> 04:11.752
And finished!

04:12.044 --> 04:14.546
Oh, no, this won't do.

04:14.546 --> 04:15.923
That's the only head we got.

04:15.923 --> 04:17.758
I mean, what I'm wearing.

04:17.758 --> 04:22.596
I'm sorry, Cara. But due to your various
and unusual proportions,

04:22.596 --> 04:25.098
no clothing will ever fit you.

04:25.098 --> 04:28.685
There's just no possible way to...
I've got it!

04:30.938 --> 04:34.566
Simply step into my 3D clothing scanner.

04:38.403 --> 04:40.656
You didn't need that hind leg anyway.

04:40.656 --> 04:43.367
Now, we'll take your exact measurements.

04:45.035 --> 04:49.456
Good Lord!
Encode them in a strand of RNA.

04:50.123 --> 04:53.627
Inject it into
a giant Bolivian silkworm.

04:54.795 --> 04:57.047
Let it spin its cocoon.

04:57.422 --> 05:00.300
And six weeks later, presto!

05:00.300 --> 05:03.470
We have a custom fitted silk garment.

05:07.307 --> 05:10.727
Thanks, but it's a little
Soviet brutalist for me.

05:10.727 --> 05:13.689
That's because you are looking
at the wrong side.

05:15.816 --> 05:18.610
This is spectacular.

05:18.610 --> 05:21.280
I never expected
to love something so much

05:21.280 --> 05:23.156
that was excreted from a moth.

05:27.160 --> 05:29.371
<i>Scientists and scienticians,</i>

05:29.371 --> 05:33.500
<i>I'm proud to present the finalists
for this year's Inventors' Award.</i>

05:33.709 --> 05:36.003
<i>First up, Dr. Bubblegum Tate,</i>

05:36.003 --> 05:39.673
<i>and his postdoctoral fellow,
Sweet Clyde Dixon.</i>

05:41.300 --> 05:45.345
Dr. Dixon and I have devised a way
to generate clean power

05:45.345 --> 05:49.808
from the billions of basketballs
discarded each year by the Big 12.

05:59.902 --> 06:03.739
<i>Next up, last year's winner,
Professor Ogden Wernstrom.</i>

06:03.739 --> 06:05.866
Wernstrom!

06:06.742 --> 06:11.205
Discarded doomsday devices
pose a grave environmental risk.

06:11.205 --> 06:14.333
So I've invented a way
of reprogramming them

06:14.333 --> 06:17.252
into lovable companions for the elderly.

06:21.673 --> 06:23.091
Aww!

06:23.967 --> 06:25.802
Come along, Explodey.

06:28.013 --> 06:29.056
<i>And last up...</i>

06:31.016 --> 06:33.852
<i>...Professor Hubert J. Farnsworth.</i>

06:34.603 --> 06:37.898
<i>Colleagues, you witness history tonight.</i>

06:37.898 --> 06:42.986
<i>The technology to recycle the dead
back to semi-normal life.</i>

06:50.369 --> 06:53.622
<i>It's a scientific leap for humanity.</i>

06:53.622 --> 06:54.706
<i>Questions?</i>

06:54.706 --> 06:57.626
Who made that dress? It's fabulous.

06:57.626 --> 07:01.505
<i>Did you not hear what I said?
I brought a human back to life!</i>

07:01.505 --> 07:04.883
But that gown
brings sexy back to science.

07:05.342 --> 07:09.596
Are there any questions about my
invention and not the damn dress?

07:11.348 --> 07:13.183
<i>And now, to announce the winner.</i>

07:13.183 --> 07:17.396
<i>In the spirit of recycling,
we're reusing last year's envelope.</i>

07:19.565 --> 07:23.277
<i>And the winner was Ogden Wernstrom.</i>

07:33.620 --> 07:36.206
Cara! Over here. Show us the dress.

07:36.582 --> 07:40.919
Oh, what's going on?
The photon pressure is knocking me over.

07:40.919 --> 07:43.672
Who are you wearing?
You look incredible.

07:43.672 --> 07:45.465
It's a brand new designer.

07:45.465 --> 07:48.135
- The Professor.
- Wha...

07:53.307 --> 07:57.144
All my life,
I've pursued my first love, science.

07:57.477 --> 07:59.980
But my career has come to naught.

07:59.980 --> 08:04.026
It's time to admit I should have pursued
my first love,

08:04.651 --> 08:05.694
fashion.

08:09.573 --> 08:13.035
- Oh, my.
- That'll look better on me.

08:23.587 --> 08:27.382
I've got a midlife crisis ponytail
for a Hubert Farnsworth.

08:27.382 --> 08:29.760
It's pronounced Hugh-bear.

08:29.760 --> 08:30.886
It is?

08:32.012 --> 08:36.475
Gorgeous, like a desiccated Zac Posen.

08:36.600 --> 08:39.728
Hugh-bear, I'm going to make you a star.

08:39.728 --> 08:43.065
I've made a few calls.
You're on a magazine cover, baby.

08:44.191 --> 08:45.192
Oh, my.

08:45.192 --> 08:50.781
I'm on the cover of <i>Vague.</i>
My mother would be so confused.

08:52.658 --> 08:56.036
It's Gladys Lennox,
the world-famous paramecium,

08:56.036 --> 08:58.789
star of <i>Mitosis, Lies and Videotape.</i>

08:58.789 --> 09:02.125
Is there something we can help you with,
Ms. Lennox?

09:02.125 --> 09:05.796
I saw the dress you made
and I must have one.

09:06.505 --> 09:08.465
I just love the stitch work.

09:08.465 --> 09:10.926
Thank you. It's holding my neck on.

09:10.926 --> 09:12.594
Cara's one of a kind.

09:12.594 --> 09:16.431
Not like those mass-produced
Frankensteins you see nowadays.

09:16.431 --> 09:18.976
Being boneless, clothing never fits me.

09:18.976 --> 09:21.520
It's like trying to put pants
on a waterbed.

09:21.520 --> 09:23.856
I once got the pants off a waterbed,

09:23.856 --> 09:27.109
but that's a very long,
very dirty story.

09:28.735 --> 09:33.740
I can make you an outfit, Ms. Lennox,
but it's a slow, meticulous process.

09:34.241 --> 09:35.742
Also expensive.

09:35.742 --> 09:39.496
Money's no object.
I have contractile vacuoles full of it.

09:42.541 --> 09:44.668
Gol'durned cytoplasm.

09:44.668 --> 09:46.378
Yeah! That's it!

09:46.378 --> 09:49.882
Make sweet asexual love to the scanner.

09:49.882 --> 09:51.884
No, don't shake your money maker.

09:51.884 --> 09:54.928
Give me less of that.
Don't work it, baby.

09:58.515 --> 10:02.311
Ooh. I want to give myself an award
for looking at that dress.

10:02.311 --> 10:04.396
Who are you wearing, Gladys?

10:04.396 --> 10:07.566
What, this little thing?
It's from the House of Professor.

10:08.025 --> 10:10.944
- Get me the Professor.
- Get me the Professor.

10:10.944 --> 10:12.571
Get me the Professor.

10:13.113 --> 10:14.114
The Professor.

10:17.451 --> 10:19.745
Tim Gunn here at Milan Fashion Week.

10:19.745 --> 10:22.497
Today, the hot, new, old designer

10:22.497 --> 10:25.542
whose name is on everyone's
silicone-filled lips:

10:25.542 --> 10:27.628
Hugh-bear Farntsvirt.

10:30.088 --> 10:31.965
Please, no photons.

10:40.224 --> 10:41.225
Two minutes.

10:41.225 --> 10:46.230
I'm so nervous, and I can barely move
in these high heeled slippers.

10:46.730 --> 10:48.899
How am I supposed to walk Marcelle?

10:50.526 --> 10:53.946
Not to worry.
Zoidberg will walk your leggy snake.

11:00.744 --> 11:03.539
<i>Welcome to the fashion event
of the millennium!</i>

11:03.539 --> 11:08.627
<i>We call it Haute Cocoon,
by the Professor. Enjoy.</i>

11:14.675 --> 11:15.759
I'll be...

11:21.849 --> 11:26.854
Shock me back to life with
a defibrillator because I am dead.

11:29.314 --> 11:31.233
I'm Zoidberg. I'm on the list.

11:32.818 --> 11:36.071
Sorry, we're full.
The anteater can come in, though.

11:37.948 --> 11:40.075
But I'm on the list. Right there.

11:40.993 --> 11:41.994
Now you're not.

11:41.994 --> 11:43.537
You're dressed like some sort of

11:43.537 --> 11:46.164
underpaid lobster doctor
from outer space.

11:46.164 --> 11:48.959
But I can't afford nicer clothings.

11:49.334 --> 11:50.627
Then beat it.

11:53.964 --> 11:58.802
I've never felt so worthless.
I'll just throw myself in the garbage.

12:01.680 --> 12:04.349
You can't come in our dumpster
what looking like that.

12:04.349 --> 12:06.226
Not during Fashion Week.

12:19.031 --> 12:20.949
You're a hit, Professor!

12:20.949 --> 12:24.995
You'll be invited to every party,
every soirÃ©e, every orgy.

12:24.995 --> 12:28.916
