Who's gonna stop me?

12:30.459 --> 12:32.127
Zoidberg! What are you doing?

12:32.127 --> 12:33.212
Jumping.

12:34.379 --> 12:36.965
- No, stop.
- You don't get it.

12:36.965 --> 12:41.887
Your fabulous clothing just makes
the other 99% of us sad and jealous.

12:44.139 --> 12:47.726
I'm sick of dressing in
factory reject chef's jackets

12:47.726 --> 12:49.978
and children's flip flops.

12:49.978 --> 12:52.064
Goodbye, fancy friends.

12:53.649 --> 12:55.317
No!

12:55.901 --> 12:57.110
Don't do it!

13:01.114 --> 13:03.784
Zoidberg, don't kill yourself!

13:03.784 --> 13:08.789
What? No, I'm just going underwater
where the fashion standards are lower.

13:11.375 --> 13:14.294
Excuse me,
the fashion standards aren't lower.

13:14.294 --> 13:17.047
Why, look at the flatlock seam
on my clam shells.

13:28.100 --> 13:30.352
Professor, when you started your line,

13:30.352 --> 13:33.063
you were proud the clothes
could fit anyone.

13:33.063 --> 13:35.858
But it's only the wealthy
who can enjoy them.

13:35.858 --> 13:37.651
I feel for you, Zoidberg.

13:37.651 --> 13:41.697
But there's simply no way
to mass produce my cocoon patterns.

13:41.697 --> 13:43.740
And moth chow isn't free.

13:46.493 --> 13:48.620
But isn't the difference between couture

13:48.620 --> 13:51.623
and ready-to-wear
just a matter of technology?

13:51.623 --> 13:53.834
Well, I suppose it is.

13:53.834 --> 13:56.044
I've never told anyone this,

13:56.044 --> 14:00.549
but it's been my lifelong dream
to be a famous scientist.

14:00.549 --> 14:04.595
Perhaps I could use science
to bring fashion to the masses,

14:04.595 --> 14:07.306
but no, I'm afraid it's completely...

14:07.306 --> 14:09.057
Eureka!

14:09.057 --> 14:12.477
Bender, hand me that hat
from my new October line.

14:17.816 --> 14:21.028
Fly, fly, my pretties!

14:27.159 --> 14:31.538
Welcome to <i>Good Morning Tonight.</i>
Or as I like to say, <i>Good Mor-night.</i>

14:33.165 --> 14:35.250
I will destroy you
and your entire species

14:35.250 --> 14:37.377
if you continue to combine those words.

14:37.377 --> 14:41.256
This mor-night, we have a very special
guest in the studio.

14:41.256 --> 14:44.801
Legendary fashion designer,
Hugh-bear Farntsvirt.

14:49.223 --> 14:52.518
Morbo has heard through his earpiece
that this wrinkly human

14:52.518 --> 14:55.729
now offers a clothing line
for a broader audience.

14:55.729 --> 14:57.147
Indeed I do.

14:57.147 --> 15:00.734
You see, I've created a variant
on the giant moth

15:00.734 --> 15:02.736
I use for my couture line.

15:04.821 --> 15:08.742
For a low monthly price,
you get a hanger moth for your closet.

15:08.867 --> 15:13.038
And it extrudes a bespoke
tailored outfit every day.

15:13.038 --> 15:16.834
They're essentially high-speed
3D silk printers.

15:16.834 --> 15:18.919
Morbo demands a demonstration!

15:26.969 --> 15:29.721
This just in. I look fabulous.

15:29.721 --> 15:33.350
These slacks really flatter
Morbo's pulsating buttocks.

15:33.350 --> 15:34.977
How do I wash them?

15:34.977 --> 15:36.728
Oh, no need to wash anything.

15:36.728 --> 15:39.648
The outfits fall apart
after one day's use.

15:39.648 --> 15:42.568
But they'd be out of fashion
by then anyway.

15:42.568 --> 15:46.738
Each night, just dispose of them
in my patented fash-can.

15:51.785 --> 15:54.496
It's fast fashion at its fastiest.

15:54.496 --> 15:56.331
Where do the clothes go?

15:56.331 --> 15:58.834
Who knows? Who cares?

15:58.834 --> 16:00.460
Tell us, Professor Farntsvirt,

16:00.460 --> 16:02.796
how can our viewers
get your new clothing line?

16:02.796 --> 16:06.758
Just leave the window open
and the light on.

16:41.752 --> 16:45.130
Great look, Zoidberg. Very today.

16:45.130 --> 16:46.215
Thank you.

16:46.215 --> 16:48.926
Though, to be honest,
I liked yesterday's even better.

16:48.926 --> 16:50.177
Would it be possible

16:50.177 --> 16:51.887
- to get those pants back?
- No!

16:51.887 --> 16:54.473
They made my hips look like I had hips.

16:54.473 --> 16:57.100
- But I threw them in the fash-can.
- Forget it.

16:57.100 --> 16:59.811
Yesterday's pants
are completely out of date.

16:59.811 --> 17:02.856
Hugh-bear, Zoidberg knows what he likes,

17:02.856 --> 17:05.901
and that means he has something
even better than fashion.

17:05.901 --> 17:07.569
He has style.

17:07.569 --> 17:10.697
- Wha...
- Plus, isn't it more environmental

17:10.697 --> 17:13.742
to wear a piece of clothing twice
before you throw it away?

17:15.327 --> 17:19.289
I would gladly crawl in after them,
but I can't fit in the fash-can.

17:19.289 --> 17:20.624
Anything can fit.

17:20.624 --> 17:25.379
The fash-can is a multi-dimensional
wormhole through space and time

17:25.379 --> 17:27.381
and probably some other things.

17:27.381 --> 17:29.383
Allow me to demonstrate.

17:29.383 --> 17:31.677
Jessica. Oh, Jessica.

17:34.471 --> 17:36.723
Go on, girl. Get your peanut.

17:43.772 --> 17:46.275
Professor! That's horrible!

17:46.275 --> 17:50.404
Relax. I get a new pet every day
to go with my outfits.

17:50.404 --> 17:52.197
That's slightly worse.

17:52.197 --> 17:54.741
It's simply too dangerous
to pass through

17:54.741 --> 17:58.287
a trillion light-year wormhole
for a pair of pants.

17:58.287 --> 18:01.373
Why, the temporal distortion alone
could render you...

18:07.754 --> 18:09.006
Whoa.

18:09.006 --> 18:10.632
That's what I was gonna say.

18:10.632 --> 18:12.843
We're coming out of the wormhole.

18:12.843 --> 18:14.261
There's a planet ahead!

18:22.811 --> 18:24.021
Shmoly-moly!

18:24.021 --> 18:26.273
If any civilization was here,

18:26.273 --> 18:29.067
it's been smothered
by the Professor's clothes.

18:29.067 --> 18:33.322
The devastation is too much.
It's beyond comprehension.

18:34.406 --> 18:35.407
My pants!

18:42.998 --> 18:46.168
All right, let's snag Zoidberg's pants
and get out of here.

18:46.168 --> 18:48.295
Bender, deploy the space hooker.

18:48.295 --> 18:49.963
Deploy her? I barely know her.

18:51.465 --> 18:53.425
Just kidding. I'm a regular customer.

19:01.141 --> 19:02.893
It's a total shirt storm.

19:02.893 --> 19:04.937
What do we do? Panic?

19:07.564 --> 19:10.567
A flock of Canadian bras got sucked
into the engine.

19:10.567 --> 19:12.069
We'll have to crash land.

19:17.115 --> 19:18.408
And we're fine.

19:18.408 --> 19:22.621
I believe we were spared for one reason,
and one reason only.

19:22.621 --> 19:25.541
To save Zoidberg's pants. Come on.

19:28.085 --> 19:30.879
- Wuzzat?
- Moths! Huge ones!

19:30.879 --> 19:34.424
They must be feasting
on high-protein sportswear.

19:34.424 --> 19:38.762
Actually, it's not the moths
that eat clothes. It's the caterpillars.

19:38.762 --> 19:41.849
People don't know that
because they're tiny and hard to see.

19:59.116 --> 20:00.242
And we're fine.

20:01.201 --> 20:03.620
What's this metal thing
we're cowering behind?

20:03.620 --> 20:05.914
Some sort of abandoned structure.

20:05.914 --> 20:09.126
The Professor really did destroy
a civilization.

20:09.126 --> 20:12.504
It's history's most brutal crime
of fashion.

20:12.754 --> 20:16.508
Ah, my pants!
There, in that pile of crisp whites.

20:17.259 --> 20:20.679
Oh, to wear them just once more!

20:22.723 --> 20:24.892
The Professor's garbage pets.

20:24.892 --> 20:26.476
Run for your lives.

20:26.476 --> 20:29.313
No. I am a professional fashion model.

20:29.313 --> 20:31.690
We do not run. We strut.

20:31.690 --> 20:35.360
And we do not leave our comrades'
fallen pants behind.

20:35.360 --> 20:39.031
Sounds good. We'll meet you in the ship.
And by meet you, I mean, ditch you.

20:46.371 --> 20:48.207
Cara, look out!

20:59.551 --> 21:01.929
Everybody on board.
Before we get buried.

21:07.476 --> 21:08.769
Jump!

21:11.396 --> 21:15.317
- Hang on. You'll be okay.
- But my grip is crumpling the pants.

21:15.317 --> 21:16.693
So I'll iron them.

21:16.693 --> 21:18.987
No, the material's too cheap.

21:18.987 --> 21:21.490
It won't stand up
to even the lowest setting.

21:21.490 --> 21:23.867
I'll wear them wrinkled.
I can pull it off.

21:23.867 --> 21:25.077
Don't be a fool.

21:25.077 --> 21:29.915
What is one life against
a completely decent pair of pants?

21:30.666 --> 21:31.792
Goodbye.

21:32.501 --> 21:35.087
Cara. No!

21:49.393 --> 21:50.936
Oh, good, you're back.

21:50.936 --> 21:55.732
I can toss yesterday's conquistador
ensemble without damaging the ship.

22:00.028 --> 22:02.656
Stop! We saw
where the clothes are going.

22:02.656 --> 22:04.950
You've wiped out an entire planet.

22:04.950 --> 22:06.660
Wiped out, you say?

22:06.660 --> 22:10.163
Well, if everyone is already dead,
I don't see the problem.

22:10.163 --> 22:14.042
Someone might still be alive
under all those vegan leather pants.

22:14.042 --> 22:17.087
Those are not breathable.
You gotta do something!

22:17.296 --> 22:19.756
Very well.

22:20.424 --> 22:23.302
The ship's log
should hold the space time coordinates

22:23.302 --> 22:25.053
of the planet you came from.

22:25.053 --> 22:27.931
I'll send them a jaws of life
or something.

22:29.057 --> 22:31.727
What is it? Something surprising?

22:31.727 --> 22:33.854
The planet you went to was...

22:34.354 --> 22:36.315
...was Earth!

22:38.025 --> 22:39.526
But that's our planet, right?

22:39.526 --> 22:41.862
And we're not buried
under miles of laundry.

22:41.862 --> 22:43.947
Don't you see, you imbecile?

22:43.947 --> 22:45.782
No, sir, I'm afraid I don't.

22:45.782 --> 22:48.368
It's Earth in the future.

22:48.368 --> 22:52.331
We sent the clothes to our own future!

22:59.630 --> 23:03.258
You finally did it,
you fast fashionistas!

23:03.258 --> 23:05.761
Damn you all to TJ Maxx!

23:06.512 --> 23:09.765
What kind of world have we left
for our children?

23:09.765 --> 23:11.183
Or their children?

23:11.183 --> 23:12.935
Or their children's children?

23:12.935 --> 23:16.021
Wait, how far into the future
did we send the clothes?

23:16.146 --> 23:17.606
What time is it?
